ire, England":"Church Minshull, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ward","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: occupational name for a watchman or guard, from Middle English <i>ward</i> ‘watchman, guard’ (Old English <i>weard</i>, used as both an agent noun and an abstract noun).","English: occupational name from Middle English <i>warde</i> ‘armed guard’ (Old English <i>weard</i> ‘watching, guarding’), with the same meaning as 1 above.","Irish: shortened form of <b>McWard</b>, an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac an Bhaird</b> ‘son of the poet’. The surname occurs throughout Ireland, where three different branches of the family are known as professional poets."],"variants":[{"name":"Warshawsky","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Meyer, Ari, Hyman.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from the city of Warsaw (Polish <i>Warszawa</i>), which became the capital of Poland at the end of the 16th century, after the destruction of Kraków by fire.","Americanized form of Polish <b>Warszawski</b>, a cognate of 1 above."]},{"name":"Wardman","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): occupational name from Middle English <i>wardman</i>, either in the general sense ‘watchman, guard’ (compare   Ward  ) or in the administrative sense ‘representative of a ward within a borough’."]},{"name":"Warde","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Cormac, Donal.","Irish: variant of   Ward  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":5,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Lady Margaret Ward of Minshull was born in 1377, in Church Minshull, Cheshire, England as the daughter of John Ward of Minshull. She married Nicholas Hesketh in 1389. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1416, in Rufford, Lancashire, England, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1377–1417":"1377–1416","1377–1416":"1377–1416","1407–1459":"1407–1459","–Male":"Surnud","1459":"1459","1389":"1389","1377":"1377","1382":"1382","1407":"1407","1417":"1416","1416":"1416","Rufford, Lancashire, England":"Rufford, Lancashire, England","Church Minshull, Cheshire, England":"Church Minshull, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1377–1417":"1377–1416","1377–1416":"1377